  "prompt": "What is creamy layer?",
  "response": "The term \"creamy layer\" refers to a socio-economic concept used primarily in India. It identifies a segment within the Other Backward Classes (OBC) that has become relatively affluent and is therefore considered to be more advanced than the rest of the OBC community. \n\nIn the context of reservations (affirmative action policies) in education and employment, the creamy layer is excluded from receiving these benefits to ensure that the advantages reach those who are genuinely disadvantaged. \n\nThe criteria for identifying the creamy layer can include income, educational qualifications, and the occupation of family members, among other factors. The intent behind defining the creamy layer is to prevent the misuse of reservations by those who do not need them due to their higher socio-economic status. \n\nThis concept is important in discussions about social justice, affirmative action, and equitable access to opportunities in India.",
